<bibRefCitation id="48685E99FF9DFB73FD61F8FEFC78BDF5" author="Moreno, S. &amp; Karremans, A. P." box="[645,927,1914,1936]" pageId="3" pageNumber="280" pagination="21" refId="ref2451" refString="Moreno, S. &amp; Karremans, A. P. (2018) Masdevallia racemosa. Species Orchidacearum 2 (2): LCDP 21." type="journal article" year="2018">Moreno &amp; Karremans (2018)</bibRefCitation>
with their permission.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF6CFF1AFDFCB80C" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
Plant epiphytic, litophytic or terrestrial, repent. Roots slender, 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FCAFFF1AFC34BADC" box="[843,979,158,185]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="0.7" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.8 mm</quantity>
in diameter when dried. Ramicauls stout, erect (0.5–) 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FEECFF46FE63BAB8" box="[264,388,194,221]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.8" metricValueMax="3.8" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="2.8" valueMax="3.8" valueMin="1.8">1.8–3.8 cm</quantity>
long, 1.0– 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FE18FF46FDA2BAB8" box="[508,581,194,221]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="1.8">1.8 cm</quantity>
in diameter, enclosed by 2-3 tubular sheaths. Leaves erect, thickly coriaceous, petiolate, lanceolate, acute, base narrowly cuneate into a blackish petiole, (0.6–) 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FBD4FF62FB56BB64" box="[1072,1201,230,257]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.6" valueMin="1.9">1.9–2.6 cm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FAE4FF62FA6CBB64" box="[1280,1419,230,257]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="1.2" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.9">0.9–1.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter; the blade (2.5–) 4.3–6.2 × (0.7–) 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FDBCFE8EFD31BB40" box="[600,726,266,293]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="2.1" metricValueMin="1.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="1.7" valueMax="2.1" valueMin="1.3">1.3–2.1 cm</quantity>
. Inflorescence loose, successively one to several flowered raceme, (9.2–)19.5–29.0 cm long; peduncle slender, erect, (6.8–)13.5–25.0 cm long, maroon. Ovary maroon, sulcate, 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FAB3FEAAFF53BB08" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="4.0" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="3.5">3.5–4.5 mm</quantity>
long. Flowers one or two open at one time; pedicel 2.0– 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FCC9FED6FC9CBB08" box="[813,891,338,365]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="2.1">2.1 cm</quantity>
; sepals reddish-orange, sparsely hirsute adaxially; dorsal sepal obovate, 2.0–2.8 × 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FE02FEF2FD95BBF4" box="[486,626,374,401]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.025" metricValueMax="1.1" metricValueMin="0.95" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="1.025" valueMax="1.1" valueMin="0.95">0.95–1.1 cm</quantity>
, connate to the lateral sepals for 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FC3CFEF2FBB0BBF4" box="[984,1111,374,401]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="1.7" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="1.6">1.6–1.8 cm</quantity>
, forming a cylindrical sepaline tube, free portion obtuse, apiculate, three veined; lateral sepals forming an obovate, obtuse, emarginate synsepal, 2.7– 3.0 × 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FF2EFE3AFEABBBBC" box="[202,332,446,473]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="cm" value="1.75" valueMax="1.9" valueMin="1.6">1.6–1.9 cm</quantity>
. Petals orange, oblong-elliptic, slightly falcate, obtuse, the labellar half with an elliptical callus, 5.0 mm × 2.0– 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FEE7FE66FEBCBB98" box="[259,347,482,509]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
. Lip white with yellow apical margins, obovate, obtuse, straight, margin undulate, sulcate between a pair of low calli, base truncate, 6.0–6.5 × 1.6–2.0 mm. Column whitish-yellow, margin erose, slightly arched toward the apex, 5.0– 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FECEFDAEFE66B820" box="[298,385,554,581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FE2FFDAEFDC5B820" box="[459,546,554,581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
in diameter. Anther cap obovoid, papillose, 1.2 × 1.0 mm. Pollinia 2, obovoid, laterally compressed, 1.2 × 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FE5AFDCAFDF0B80C" box="[446,535,590,617]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="64E370E3FF9AFB74FF59FDF6FA4BB9ED" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF59FDF6FA4BB9ED" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF59FDF6FEA4B8E9" bold="true" box="[189,323,626,652]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FEAFFDF6FDADB8E9" box="[331,586,626,652]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mirandae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FEAFFDF6FDADB8E9" box="[331,586,626,652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia mirandae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the previously monotypic 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FC1AFDF6FAAAB8E9" authorityName="Woolward" authorityYear="1896" box="[1022,1357,626,653]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Racemosae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FC1AFDF6FB6FB8E9" box="[1022,1160,626,652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia</emphasis>
sect. 
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FB29FDF7FAAAB8E9" box="[1229,1357,627,652]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Racemosae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. With it only other member, 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FE8DFD13FE1BB8D5" authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1845" box="[361,508,663,688]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FE8DFD13FE1BB8D5" box="[361,508,663,688]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">M. racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it shares the repent habit, the loose multiflowered inflorescence that is much longer than the leaves, the eye-catching medium-sized red-orange flowers, and the sepals forming a sepaline tube for most of their length (
<figureCitation id="B4C23FEDFF9AFB74FED8FD5AFE6CB89D" box="[316,395,734,760]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1876,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1852]" captionTargetId="figure-17@2.[151,1436,190,1852]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Plate of Masdevallia mirandae. A. Habit. B. Ramicaul with leaf. C. Detail of ramicaul bracts. D. Flower, dorsal view. E. Flower, ventral view. F. Detail of the inner surface of sepals. G. Lip, adaxial view. H. Ovary and column, side view. I. Petal, adaxial view. Photographs by Robinson Galindo-Tarazona (A–F) and Alejandro Zuluaga (G–I; from a prickled specimen), based on the type specimen." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425105" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425105/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation id="B4C23FEDFF9AFB74FE57FD5AFE24B89D" box="[435,451,734,760]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1877,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-21@3.[151,1436,190,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Plate of Masdevallia racemosa. A. Habit. B. Flower. C. Dissected perianth. D. Column, ventral view. E. Ovary with column and lip. F. Pollinia and anther cap. Reproduced from Moreno &amp; Karremans (2018) with their permission." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5425107" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5425107/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">3</figureCitation>
). The new species can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FC35FD5BFB82B89D" authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1845" box="[977,1125,735,760]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FC35FD5BFB82B89D" box="[977,1125,735,760]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">M. racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the blackish (vs reddish) petiole, the obtuse and apiculate dorsal sepal (vs. acute and acuminate), the hispid inner surface of the lateral sepals (vs glabrous), and the 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FEB1FCA2FE72B924" box="[341,405,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
long, oblong-elliptic, obtuse petals (vs 
<quantity id="EB018E8DFF9AFB74FCADFCA2FC46B924" box="[841,929,806,833]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3-4 mm</quantity>
long, lanceolate and acute). The distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FF6CFCCEFE60B901" authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1845" box="[136,391,842,868]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF6CFCCEFE60B901" box="[136,391,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is so far restricted to the Central Cordillera of the Andes in The Puracé National Natural Park, while 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FF29FCEBFEB9B9ED" box="[205,350,878,904]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mirandae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF29FCEBFEB9B9ED" box="[205,350,878,904]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">M. mirandae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known to occur in the Western Cordillera in The Farallones de Cali National Natural Park.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="64E370E3FF9AFB74FF59FC16FED3BF39" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF59FC16FB37B9B4" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF59FC16FEAFB9C9" bold="true" box="[189,328,914,940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Etymology:</emphasis>
Named after Julia 
<collectingRegion id="EE3DED8AFF9AFB74FDFAFC16FD9AB9C9" box="[542,637,914,940]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Miranda</collectingRegion>
Londoño who served as the Director of the Colombian National Natural Parks and dedicated more than fifteen years to the conservation of the Colombian protected areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF59FC5EFE49BE05" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF59FC5EFE50B991" bold="true" box="[189,439,986,1012]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Habitat and ecology:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FE5BFC5EFD5BB991" box="[447,700,986,1012]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mirandae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FE5BFC5EFD5BB991" box="[447,700,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia mirandae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is, as far as is currently known, endemic to the Western Cordillera of the Andes in The Farallones de Cali National Natural Park where it is restricted to a small area in the Andean cloud forest–Paramo transition around 3000 (to 3400) m in elevation, growing as an epiphyte, lithophyte or terrestrial close to small creeks and rivers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF59FBEEFDFFBEA8" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF59FBEEFEA4BEE1" bold="true" box="[189,323,1130,1156]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Phenology:</emphasis>
In the field, 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FE32FBEEFD34BEE1" box="[470,723,1130,1156]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mirandae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FE32FBEEFD34BEE1" box="[470,723,1130,1156]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia mirandae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found blooming in July and December. The long-lived flowers open in succession; therefore the flowering season is likely to be several months long. Perhaps even all year round, as occurs with 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FE9BFB37FDF6BEA9" authorityName="Lindley" authorityYear="1845" box="[383,529,1203,1228]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="racemosa">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FE9BFB37FDF6BEA9" box="[383,529,1203,1228]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">M. racemosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2C462368FF9AFB74FF59FB52FED3BF39" blockId="4.[136,1452,158,1372]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FF59FB52FE53BE95" bold="true" box="[189,436,1238,1264]" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Conservation status:</emphasis>
Following the IUCN criteria we categorize 
<taxonomicName id="EBF958EBFF9AFB74FC45FB52FB7ABE95" box="[929,1181,1238,1264]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Masdevallia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="281" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mirandae">
<emphasis id="1E8DFF7AFF9AFB74FC45FB52FB7ABE95" box="[929,1181,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="281">Masdevallia mirandae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as Data Deficient given that lack of information to make an assessment. However, despite being found in a National Natural Park, this plant grows in areas that are severely affected by illegal mining activities which directly impact the small creeks where the species thrives.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
